  "doc_id": "46604",
  "text": "Parameters that can be determined are core body temperature (°C) and brain temperature (°C). Normal body temperature for rats is between 37 and 38°C and for mice is between 36.5 and 38°C. Brain temperature is usually considered a \"central\" temperature, and in the absence of intracranial pathology, changes in brain temperature can be estimated by measuring changes in body core temperature. However, in cases of severe cerebral injury, the estimates yielded by such measurements may be inaccurate. A positive brain-body temperature gradient (brain temperature > body temperature) was observed in freely moving rats [CITATION_1] and mice. [CITATION_2] In anesthetized states, possibly due to the suppression of metabolic heat production by the anesthetic agent as well as effective heat exchange with the environment through the head, a negative brain-body temperature gradient (brain temperature < body temperature) has been observed in rats. In awake freely moving rats, temperature in hippocampus and piriform cortex can decrease 0.5°C over a 1 h period of sleep and quiet wakefulness, and then increase 1.5°C when the rat is actively exploring. [CITATION_3] ",
